Generative World Models for Autonomous Planetary Navigation (GWMN): A Rigorous Mathematical Framework

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Affiliation: Independent Researcher / Future AI & Space Systems
Date: March 2026
Status: Final Theoretical Draft

---

Abstract

Planetary rovers must operate under severe communication delays, partial observability, and strict safety constraints. Current autonomy systems are reactive and lack the ability to simulate future outcomes or learn from experience. This work presents a comprehensive mathematical framework for Generative World Model Navigation (GWMN), in which an agent builds a latent representation of its environment, performs multi‑step predictive simulation, and selects actions to optimize a multi‑objective cost while respecting safety constraints. We formalize the problem as a Constrained Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (CPOMDP) with a learned latent dynamics model. We introduce a Latent Lyapunov Barrier to ensure forward invariance of safe sets despite model errors. We derive compounding error bounds for latent trajectory prediction, showing that under mild contraction assumptions the total variation distance grows at most linearly with horizon, with improved constants when the dynamics are contractive. Using PAC‑Bayes theory adapted to non‑i.i.d. planetary data, we provide non‑asymptotic generalization bounds that quantify epistemic uncertainty. Finally, we analyze the computational complexity of the planner under hardware resource constraints, proving that an \alpha-optimal action can be found within a given onboard compute budget. Together, these results provide a foundation for certifiably safe, adaptive planetary exploration.

