2. Literature Review

2.1 Model‑Based Reinforcement Learning

World models (Ha & Schmidhuber, 2018) learn a latent dynamics model from observations and use it for planning. DreamerV3 (Hafner et al., 2023) scales this to complex domains by training a recurrent state‑space model (RSSM). Recent extensions such as DreamerNav (2025) adapt world models to LIDAR‑based navigation, achieving high success rates on simulated robots. Navigation World Models (CVPR 2025) demonstrate controllable future prediction for driving. However, these works focus on empirical performance and lack theoretical guarantees on safety and generalization.

2.2 Safe Reinforcement Learning

Constrained Markov Decision Processes (CMDPs) (Altman, 1999) provide a framework for optimizing a reward subject to cumulative cost constraints. Recent work combines CMDPs with Lyapunov functions to ensure stability (Chow et al., 2019). Control Lyapunov‑Barrier Functions (Ames et al., 2019) offer a unified approach to safety and stability in robotics. Our approach extends these ideas to the POMDP setting with a learned latent model.

2.3 PAC‑Bayes and Generalization

PAC‑Bayes theory (McAllester, 1999) offers bounds on the generalization error of stochastic predictors. It has been applied to reinforcement learning (Fard et al., 2012) but rarely to world models for planetary navigation. We adapt PAC‑Bayes to bound the prediction error of the latent dynamics on unseen terrains, accounting for temporal dependence via mixing coefficients.

2.4 Computational Constraints in Space Systems

Onboard processors on rovers (e.g., RAD750) have limited computational throughput. Emerging processors like HPSC (High‑Performance Spaceflight Computing) offer greater performance, but certification constraints remain tight. Techniques such as sparse sampling (Kearns et al., 2002) and efficient model‑based planning (Moerland et al., 2020) are essential. We incorporate a resource‑aware analysis into our framework.

