4. Theoretical Analysis

4.1 Compounding Error in Latent Trajectory Prediction

Let P^t(z_t \mid z_0, a_{0:t-1}) be the true latent transition distribution induced by the environment and the encoder, and \hat{P}^t be the distribution generated by the world model using p_\psi. We bound the total variation (TV) distance after H steps.

Lemma 1 (Single‑Step Error). Assume that for all z, a,

D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( P(\cdot \mid z, a) \,\|\, \hat{P}(\cdot \mid z, a) \big) \leq \epsilon.

Lemma 2 (Compounding Error with Contraction). If, in addition, the true transition kernel is a contraction in TV with factor \rho < 1 (i.e., for any two distributions \mu_1, \mu_2 on \mathcal{Z}, D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\int P(\cdot \mid z, a) \mu_1(dz), \int P(\cdot \mid z, a) \mu_2(dz)) \leq \rho D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_1, \mu_2)), then for any initial latent state z_0 and action sequence a_{0:H-1},

D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( P^H(\cdot \mid z_0, a_{0:H-1}) \,\|\, \hat{P}^H(\cdot \mid z_0, a_{0:H-1}) \big) \leq \epsilon \cdot \frac{1 - \rho^H}{1 - \rho}.

Proof sketch. By induction. For H=1 the bound holds. For H>1, write:

P^H(z_H) = \int P^{H-1}(z_{H-1}) \, P(z_H \mid z_{H-1}, a_{H-1}) \, dz_{H-1},

and similarly for \hat{P}^H. Using the triangle inequality and the contraction property, we obtain:

D_{\mathrm{TV}}(P^H, \hat{P}^H) \leq \rho D_{\mathrm{TV}}(P^{H-1}, \hat{P}^{H-1}) + \epsilon.

Solving the recurrence yields the geometric series. ∎

Remark. The contraction assumption holds for many dynamical systems when the latent space is sufficiently structured (e.g., linear systems with stable eigenvalues). Even when not exactly contractive, the bound reduces to the linear H\epsilon case (by setting \rho=1).

4.2 Safety Certificate via Lyapunov Barrier

We now connect the latent barrier to actual safety constraints. Assume the true cost d(s,a) is bounded and Lipschitz in the latent representation, and the model error is bounded as in Lemma 2.

Theorem 1 (Safety Certificate). Suppose the latent Lyapunov barrier V satisfies the invariance condition with margin \kappa under the model dynamics. Let \delta \in (0,1) and let the model error be such that

\epsilon \cdot \frac{1 - \rho^H}{1 - \rho} \leq \frac{\kappa}{2\|V\|_\infty}.

Then, with probability at least 1-\delta, the real‑world trajectory satisfies V(z_t) \leq 0 for all t \leq H if the initial state is safe and the agent only selects actions that satisfy the model‑based invariance condition.

Proof sketch. The proof uses the TV bound to relate the model‑predicted expected Lyapunov decrement to the true decrement. By the triangle inequality,

\bigl|\mathbb{E}_{\text{true}}[V(z_{t+1}) \mid z_t, a_t] - \mathbb{E}_{\text{model}}[V(z_{t+1}) \mid z_t, a_t]\bigr| \leq \|V\|_\infty \cdot D_{\mathrm{TV}}(P, \hat{P}).

Using Lemma 2, the cumulative error over H steps is bounded by \|V\|_\infty \cdot \epsilon (1-\rho^H)/(1-\rho). The condition ensures this error is at most \kappa/2. Then the true expected decrement is at most -\kappa/2 when V(z_t) > 0, so by a concentration inequality (e.g., Azuma’s) the actual Lyapunov value remains bounded. ∎

4.3 PAC‑Bayes Generalization Bound for Non‑i.i.d. Data

Planetary data are temporally correlated. To handle this, we assume the data sequence (z_t, a_t, z_{t+1})_{t=1}^n is drawn from a stationary process with mixing coefficient \beta(m) \to 0 as m \to \infty. Define the effective sample size n_{\text{eff}} = n / \tau where \tau = \sum_{m=1}^{\infty} \beta(m) (the mixing time). Then the standard PAC‑Bayes bound can be adapted.

Theorem 2 (PAC‑Bayes for Mixing Processes). Let \ell(\theta; z,a,z') \in [0,1] be a bounded loss function. For any \delta \in (0,1), with probability at least 1-\delta over the draw of a stationary \beta-mixing sequence of length n, for all distributions Q on \Theta,

\mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[\mathcal{L}(\theta)] \leq \mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[\hat{\mathcal{L}}_n(\theta)] + \sqrt{\frac{D_{\mathrm{KL}}(Q \| P) + \log\frac{n_{\text{eff}}}{\delta}}{2n_{\text{eff}}}},

where \mathcal{L}(\theta) is the true expected loss under the stationary distribution, \hat{\mathcal{L}}_n(\theta) is the empirical loss, and n_{\text{eff}} = n / \tau with \tau the mixing time.

Proof sketch. This follows from applying the PAC‑Bayes theorem to a blocked sequence where blocks are approximately independent, using the mixing condition to bound the dependence (see, e.g., Fard et al., 2012). ∎

Implication. The bound quantifies epistemic uncertainty. As the rover collects more data, n_{\text{eff}} grows and the penalty term shrinks. The mixing time \tau captures how quickly terrain conditions decorrelate; longer mixing times require more data to achieve the same confidence.

4.4 Hardware‑Aware Planning Complexity

Let the onboard processor have a budget of C_{\text{max}} floating‑point operations per second. Planning involves evaluating K action sequences of length H. Each evaluation requires O(H \cdot d^2) operations (latent dynamics) plus the cost of encoding observations (which we denote c_{\text{enc}}). The total cost is K \cdot (H \cdot d^2 + c_{\text{enc}}). We choose K and H such that this is \leq C_{\text{max}} \cdot \Delta t for some decision interval \Delta t.

Theorem 3 (Resource‑Aware Planning). For any \alpha > 0, there exists a choice of K and H such that with probability at least 1-\delta, the action selected by the planner is \alpha-optimal in the sense that its true expected cost is within \alpha of the optimal cost, provided:

· The model error \epsilon satisfies \epsilon \leq \alpha / (2H) (or using the contraction bound),
· The number of samples n used for the PAC‑Bayes bound satisfies n \geq \tilde{\Omega}(\tau / \alpha^2) (where \tau is the mixing time),
· The computational budget C_{\text{max}} allows the chosen K and H (i.e., K \cdot H \cdot d^2 \leq C_{\text{max}} \cdot \Delta t).

Proof sketch. The result follows by combining the compounding error bound (Lemma 2) with the PAC‑Bayes generalization bound (Theorem 2) and standard sample‑complexity arguments for approximate dynamic programming (Kearns et al., 2002). The horizon H is chosen so that the discounted tail contributes at most \alpha/2. The model error and epistemic uncertainty are controlled to contribute at most \alpha/2 as well. The computational constraint determines the maximum feasible K and H; we show that for any \alpha we can select them to achieve the desired accuracy if the budget is sufficiently large. ∎

