Appendix A: Proof of Lemma 2 (Compounding Error with Contraction)

Lemma 2 (Compounding Error with Contraction).
Let P(\cdot \mid z,a) and \hat{P}(\cdot \mid z,a) be the true and learned single‑step latent transition kernels. Assume that for all z,a,

D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big(P(\cdot \mid z,a), \hat{P}(\cdot \mid z,a)\big) \le \epsilon.
\]  

Moreover, suppose the true kernel is a contraction in total variation with factor \rho < 1, i.e., for any two distributions \mu_1,\mu_2 on \mathcal{Z},

D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( \int P(\cdot \mid z,a) \mu_1(dz),\; \int P(\cdot \mid z,a) \mu_2(dz) \big) \le \rho \, D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_1,\mu_2).
\]  

Then for any initial latent state z_0 and action sequence a_0,\dots,a_{H-1},

D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big(P^H(\cdot \mid z_0, a_{0:H-1}),\; \hat{P}^H(\cdot \mid z_0, a_{0:H-1})\big) \le \epsilon \, \frac{1-\rho^H}{1-\rho}.

Proof.
We proceed by induction on H. Let \mu_0 = \delta_{z_0} (point mass). Define the true t-step distribution recursively:

\mu_t = \mathcal{T}_{t-1} \mu_{t-1}, \qquad \text{where } \mathcal{T}_{t-1}(\mu)(A) = \int P(A \mid z, a_{t-1}) \mu(dz).
\]  

Analogously, let \hat{\mu}_t be the distribution obtained by using the learned kernel \hat{P} at each step. The base case H=1 follows directly from the single‑step error bound:

D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_1, \hat{\mu}_1) \le \epsilon.

For the inductive step, assume that D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_{t-1}, \hat{\mu}_{t-1}) \le \epsilon \frac{1-\rho^{t-1}}{1-\rho}. Then

\begin{aligned}
D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_t, \hat{\mu}_t)
&= D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( \mathcal{T}_{t-1}\mu_{t-1},\; \hat{\mathcal{T}}_{t-1}\hat{\mu}_{t-1} \big) \\
&\le D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( \mathcal{T}_{t-1}\mu_{t-1},\; \mathcal{T}_{t-1}\hat{\mu}_{t-1} \big) + D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( \mathcal{T}_{t-1}\hat{\mu}_{t-1},\; \hat{\mathcal{T}}_{t-1}\hat{\mu}_{t-1} \big) \\
&\le \rho \, D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_{t-1}, \hat{\mu}_{t-1}) + \epsilon.
\end{aligned}
\]  

The first term uses the contraction property (true kernel applied to two distributions). The second term uses the fact that for any distribution \nu,

D_{\mathrm{TV}}\big( \mathcal{T}\nu,\; \hat{\mathcal{T}}\nu \big) \le \sup_{z,a} D_{\mathrm{TV}}(P(\cdot\mid z,a), \hat{P}(\cdot\mid z,a)) \le \epsilon,
\]  

because total variation is convex and the supremum bound holds for each pointwise kernel. Substituting the inductive hypothesis gives

D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_t, \hat{\mu}_t) \le \rho \cdot \epsilon \frac{1-\rho^{t-1}}{1-\rho} + \epsilon = \epsilon \frac{1-\rho^{t}}{1-\rho}.
\]  

Thus the bound holds for all t. ∎

Remark. If no contraction is assumed (\rho=1), the recurrence yields the linear bound D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu_H,\hat{\mu}_H) \le H\epsilon. The geometric bound is strictly tighter when \rho<1.

