Appendix C: Proof of Theorem 2 (PAC‑Bayes for Mixing Processes)

Theorem 2 (PAC‑Bayes for Mixing Processes).
Let \{Z_t\}_{t=1}^n be a stationary \beta-mixing sequence with mixing coefficients \beta(m) and mixing time \tau = \sum_{m=1}^\infty \beta(m). Define the effective sample size n_{\mathrm{eff}} = n / \tau. For any bounded loss function \ell(\theta; Z) \in [0,1], prior P on \Theta, and \delta \in (0,1), with probability at least 1-\delta over the draw of the sequence, for all distributions Q on \Theta,

\mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[\mathcal{L}(\theta)] \le \mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}[\hat{\mathcal{L}}_n(\theta)] + \sqrt{\frac{D_{\mathrm{KL}}(Q\|P) + \log\frac{n_{\mathrm{eff}}}{\delta}}{2n_{\mathrm{eff}}}},
\]  

where \mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{Z \sim \mu}[\ell(\theta; Z)] (the true expectation under the stationary distribution \mu), and \hat{\mathcal{L}}_n(\theta) = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{t=1}^n \ell(\theta; Z_t) is the empirical average.

Proof sketch.
The proof follows the standard PAC‑Bayes bound (McAllester, 1999) but replaces the i.i.d. assumption with a blocking technique that exploits mixing. Partition the sequence into k blocks of length b such that blocks are nearly independent. For \beta-mixing, we can choose b large enough so that the dependence between blocks decays exponentially. The effective number of independent blocks is approximately n / (2b). Then we apply the PAC‑Bayes bound to the block averages, treating each block as an independent observation. The loss per block is bounded by 1 (since the per‑step loss is in [0,1]). The mixing condition guarantees that the distribution of each block is close to the stationary distribution, with error controlled by the mixing coefficients. After accounting for the bias from block averaging, the effective sample size becomes n / \tau where \tau is the mixing time. The final bound is a standard PAC‑Bayes inequality with n_{\mathrm{eff}} in place of n. Detailed steps can be found in (Fard et al., 2012) and (Lauritzen, 2005). ∎

