Appendix E: Mathematical Background

E.1 Total Variation Distance

For two probability measures \mu, \nu on a measurable space (\mathcal{X}, \mathcal{F}),

D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu,\nu) = \sup_{A \in \mathcal{F}} |\mu(A) - \nu(A)| = \frac{1}{2} \int |\frac{d\mu}{d\lambda} - \frac{d\nu}{d\lambda}| d\lambda
\]  

for any dominating measure \lambda.

E.2 Kullback‑Leibler Divergence

D_{\mathrm{KL}}(Q \| P) = \int \log\left( \frac{dQ}{dP} \right) dQ
\]  

when Q \ll P.

E.3 Mixing Coefficients

A stationary process \{X_t\} is \beta-mixing if

\beta(m) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \sup_{A \in \sigma(X_{m+1}^\infty)} |\mathbb{P}(A \mid \mathcal{F}_1^m) - \mathbb{P}(A)| \right] \to 0 \text{ as } m\to\infty.
\]  

The mixing time is \tau = \sum_{m=0}^\infty \beta(m).

E.4 Contraction in Total Variation

A Markov kernel P is a contraction with factor \rho < 1 if for any two distributions \mu,\nu,

D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu P, \nu P) \le \rho D_{\mathrm{TV}}(\mu,\nu).
\]  

This holds, e.g., when the chain is uniformly ergodic with spectral gap 1-\rho.

E.5 Variational Free Energy

For the latent model, the evidence lower bound (ELBO) for observations o_{1:T} given actions a_{1:T-1} is:

\log p(o_{1:T} \mid a_{1:T-1}) \ge \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi(z_{1:T} \mid o_{1:T}, a_{1:T-1})} \left[ \sum_{t=1}^T \log p(o_t \mid z_t) + \sum_{t=1}^{T-1} \log p_\psi(z_{t+1} \mid z_t, a_t) - \sum_{t=1}^T \log q_\phi(z_t \mid o_t, z_{t-1}, a_{t-1}) \right].
\]  

Minimizing the negative ELBO gives the variational free energy \mathcal{F} used in Section 3.2.

